0,80],[90,90,90],[100,100,100]]", "output": "550"}, {"input": "cuboids = [[10, 20, 30], [20, 30, 40], [30, 40, 50], [40, 50, 60], [50, 60, 70], [60, 70, 80], [70, 80, 90], [80, 90, 100]]", "output": "520"}], "query": "You are an expert Python programmer. You will be given a question (problem specification) and will generate a correct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nGiven n cuboids where the dimensions of the ith cuboid is cuboids[i] = [widthi, lengthi, heighti] (0-indexed). Choose a subset of cuboids and place them on each other.\nYou can place cuboid i on cuboid j if widthi <= widthj and lengthi <= lengthj and heighti <= heightj. You can rearrange any cuboid's dimensions by rotating it to put it on another cuboid.\nReturn the maximum height of the stacked cuboids.\n \nExample 1:\n\n\nInput: cuboids = [[50,45,20],[95,37,53],[45,23,12]]\nOutput: 190\nExplanation:\nCuboid 1 is placed on the bottom with the 53x37 side facing down with height 95.\nCuboid 0 is placed next with the 45x20 side facing down with height 50.\nCuboid 2 is placed next with the 23x12 side facing down with height 45.\nThe total height is 95 + 50 + 45 = 190.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: cuboids = [[38,25,45],[76,35,3]]\nOutput: 76\nExplanation:\nYou can't place any of the cuboids on the other.\nWe choose cuboid 1 and rotate it so that the 35x3 side is facing down and its height is 76.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: cuboids = [[7,11,17],[7,17,11],[11,7,17],[11,17,7],[17,7,11],[17,11,7]]\nOutput: 102\nExplanation:\nAfter rearranging the cuboids, you can see that all cuboids have the same dimension.\nYou can place the 11x7 side down on all cuboids so their heights are 17.\nThe maximum height of stacked cuboids is 6 * 17 = 102.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nn == cuboids.length\n1 <= n <= 100\n1 <= widthi, lengthi, heighti <= 100\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxHeight(self, cuboids: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maxHeight(self, cuboids: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        # Sort each cuboid's dimensions\n        for cuboid in cuboids:\n            cuboid.sort()\n        \n        # Sort all cuboids\n        cuboids.sort()\n        \n        n = len(cuboids)\n        # dp[i] will be the maximum height we can achieve with cuboid i at the bottom\n        dp = [0] * n\n        \n        for i in range(n):\n            # The minimum height is the height of the cuboid itself\n            dp[i] = cuboids[i][2]\n            for j in range(i):\n                # Check if cuboid j can be placed on cuboid i\n                if (cuboids[j][0] <= cuboids[i][0] and \n                    cuboids[j][1] <= cuboids[i][1] and \n                    cuboids[j][2] <= cuboids[i][2]):\n                    dp[i] = max(dp[i], dp[j] + cuboids[i][2])\n        \n        # The result is the maximum value in dp array\n        return max(dp)\n```\n\nThis solution works as follows:\n\n1. **Sorting Dimensions**: Each cuboid's dimensions are sorted in ascending order. This allows us to easily compare cuboids without worrying about the order of dimensions.\n\n2. **Sorting Cuboids**: The cuboids themselves are sorted based on their dimensions. This ensures that when we iterate over the cuboids, we are always considering potential base cuboids in a non-decreasing order.\n\n3. **Dynamic Programming Array**: We use a `dp` array where `dp[i]` represents the maximum height of the stack with cuboid `i` at the bottom.\n\n4. **Filling the DP Array**: For each cuboid `i`, we initially set `dp[i]` to the height of cuboid `i` (since it could stand alone). Then, we check all previous cuboids `j` to see if cuboid `j` can be placed on cuboid `i` (i.e., all dimensions of `j` are less than or equal to those of `i`). If so, we update `dp[i]` to be the maximum of its current value and `dp[j] + cuboids[i][2]`.\n\n5. **Result**: The maximum value in the `dp` array is the answer, representing the maximum height achievable with any subset of the given cuboids stacked according to the rules.", "estimated_date": 1607817600000}